\section{Problem definition}
We study a supervised multi-class classification problem with a distribution shift between training and test data caused by feature-level noise. Each sample corresponds to an anonymous text instance represented by a pre-extracted feature vector, so the focus of this project is statistical learning rather than natural language processing.

\paragraph{Data setting.}
Let $\mathcal{D}_{\text{train}}=\{(\mathbf{x}_i,y_i)\}_{i=1}^{N}$ denote the training set, where $N=15000$, $\mathbf{x}_i \in \mathbb{R}^{1024}$ is a 1024-dimensional feature vector stored in NumPy format, and $y_i \in \{0,1,\ldots,9\}$ is the class label among 10 categories. The test set is $\mathcal{D}_{\text{test}}=\{\mathbf{x}_j^{\text{test}}\}_{j=1}^{M}$ with $M=2000$ samples. A validation set $\mathcal{D}_{\text{val}}$ is created by splitting $\mathcal{D}_{\text{train}}$ with a chosen ratio for model selection and hyper-parameter tuning.

\paragraph{Noise and distribution shift.}
A key characteristic of this project is that the training data are clean, while the test features are corrupted by random noise. Concretely, the test distribution can be viewed as
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{x}^{\text{test}} = \mathbf{x} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon},
\end{equation}
where $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$ denotes an unknown noise term injected into the feature space. This implies that the training and test data are not identically distributed, i.e.,
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{train}}(\mathbf{x},y) \neq p_{\text{test}}(\mathbf{x},y),
\end{equation}
making robustness and generalization under noise crucial for achieving high test accuracy.

\paragraph{Objective.}
Our goal is to learn a classifier $f_{\theta}: \mathbb{R}^{1024} \rightarrow \{0,\ldots,9\}$ using $\mathcal{D}_{\text{train}}$ (and $\mathcal{D}_{\text{val}}$ for selection) that performs well on the noisy test set. Performance is mainly evaluated by classification accuracy on the held-out test set provided by the course platform. Therefore, the problem can be formulated as minimizing the expected risk under the noisy test distribution:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta} \ \mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x}^{\text{test}},y)\sim p_{\text{test}}}
\left[ \mathbb{I}\big(f_{\theta}(\mathbf{x}^{\text{test}})\neq y\big) \right],
\end{equation}
where $\mathbb{I}(\cdot)$ is the indicator function.

\paragraph{Project requirements (summary).}
To address this task, we (1) compare at least three classification methods with at least two non-deep-learning models, (2) apply at least two model assessment and selection strategies to improve robustness and prevent overfitting, and (3) conduct clustering on training/validation/test features with visualization and analysis to understand the feature-space structure and the effect of noise.
```

