\paragraph{Feature-wise standardization.}
\textbf{Motivation.} The feature dimensions exhibit non-uniform scales and heterogeneous dispersion, which can cause a small subset of coordinates to dominate distance- or margin-based learning objectives and lead to unstable optimization. Standardization enforces a comparable scale across dimensions and improves numerical conditioning and model comparability across methods. \\
\textbf{Procedure.} We compute the per-dimension mean $\mu$ and standard deviation $\sigma$ on the training set only, and transform all splits (train/validation/test) via
\begin{equation}
x'_{d}=\frac{x_{d}-\mu_{d}}{\sigma_{d}+\epsilon},
\end{equation}
where $\epsilon$ is a small constant for numerical stability.

\paragraph{Outlier-aware scaling.}
\textbf{Motivation.} The feature distributions exhibit heavy-tailed behavior with frequent outliers; in such cases, mean/variance estimates can be overly influenced by extreme values, potentially degrading robustness under test-time noise. Robust scaling mitigates the impact of outliers by relying on robust location and scale statistics. \\
\textbf{Procedure.} Using training data only, we estimate the per-dimension median $m_d$ and interquartile range $\mathrm{IQR}_d$, and apply the transformation
\begin{equation}
x'_{d}=\frac{x_{d}-m_{d}}{\mathrm{IQR}_{d}+\epsilon}.
\end{equation}
The same transformation is then applied to the validation and test sets. We treat the choice between standardization and robust scaling as a preprocessing option selected based on validation performance.

\paragraph{Train-time noise augmentation.}
\textbf{Motivation.} Since the test features are corrupted by random noise, the learning problem involves a train--test distribution shift. Injecting noise during training acts as data augmentation and regularization, encouraging locally smooth decision functions and improving robustness to additive perturbations. \\
\textbf{Procedure.} During training, each input vector is perturbed as
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}+\alpha \boldsymbol{\eta}, \quad \boldsymbol{\eta}\sim\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}),
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ controls the noise intensity. The perturbation is applied only to training samples (not validation/test), and $\alpha$ is tuned using validation performance.
