```latex
\section{Methods}
We evaluate a diverse set of classifiers to study both predictive performance and robustness under feature noise. All models are trained on the preprocessed features described in Section~\ref{sec:data-preprocess}. Specifically, we apply feature scaling (standardization or robust scaling, selected on the validation set) to all methods. In addition, we use train-time noise augmentation during model fitting to improve robustness to test-time perturbations. For methods that are sensitive to the curse of dimensionality or rely on covariance estimation, we further apply PCA as a dimensionality reduction step. Consequently, we adopt two input configurations: (i) \emph{Preprocess+PCA} for KNN, LDA, and QDA, and (ii) \emph{Preprocess only} for Random Forest and the deep learning baseline.

\subsection{K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)}
KNN is a non-parametric classifier that assigns a label to a query point by majority vote among its $k$ nearest training samples under a chosen distance metric. Due to the high dimensionality of the original feature space, we perform PCA after preprocessing to obtain a compact representation, which reduces distance concentration effects and improves computational efficiency. The neighborhood size $k$ (and, if applicable, the distance metric) is tuned on the validation set.

\subsection{Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)}
LDA is a generative classifier that models class-conditional densities as Gaussians with class-specific means and a shared covariance matrix. The resulting decision rule is linear in the input features. Since covariance estimation can be unstable in high dimensions, we apply PCA after preprocessing to control the effective dimensionality and to regularize the covariance estimate. The number of retained principal components is selected using validation performance.

\subsection{Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)}
QDA generalizes LDA by allowing each class to have its own covariance matrix, yielding quadratic decision boundaries and higher flexibility. However, QDA is more sensitive to high-dimensional covariance estimation and potential noise amplification. Therefore, we train QDA on the \emph{Preprocess+PCA} representation to improve numerical stability and reduce overfitting. Hyperparameters related to regularization (if used) and the PCA dimension are chosen via validation.

\subsection{Random Forest}
Random Forest is an ensemble of decision trees trained with bootstrap sampling and random feature subsampling. This method is relatively insensitive to monotonic feature scaling and can capture nonlinear decision boundaries. We train it on the preprocessed features without PCA to preserve potentially informative coordinates and interactions. Key hyperparameters (e.g., number of trees, maximum depth, and minimum samples per leaf) are tuned on the validation set.

\subsection{Deep Neural Network Baseline}
As a deep learning baseline, we employ a multilayer perceptron (MLP) classifier operating on the preprocessed features. The network is trained with regularization techniques (e.g., weight decay and early stopping) and benefits from the proposed train-time noise augmentation to enhance robustness. Architectural and optimization hyperparameters (e.g., hidden width/depth, dropout rate, learning rate) are selected based on validation performance.
```

```latex
\section{Methods}
We consider a 10-class classification problem with input vectors $\mathbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{1024}$ and labels $y\in\{0,\dots,9\}$. All models are trained using the preprocessed data described in Section~\ref{sec:data-preprocess}. In particular, we apply feature scaling (standardization or robust scaling, selected on the validation set) and optionally employ train-time noise augmentation to improve robustness. For methods that are sensitive to high dimensionality and/or covariance estimation, we further apply PCA. Therefore, we adopt two input configurations:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Preprocess+PCA:} KNN, LDA, QDA;
    \item \textbf{Preprocess only:} Random Forest, deep neural network baseline.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Principal Component Analysis (PCA)}
Given the scaled training data matrix $\mathbf{X}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times D}$ (with $D=1024$), PCA computes an orthonormal projection matrix $\mathbf{W}_k\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times k}$ that maximizes retained variance. Let $\mathbf{\Sigma}=\frac{1}{N}\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X}$ be the empirical covariance matrix (after centering). PCA selects the top-$k$ eigenvectors of $\mathbf{\Sigma}$:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\Sigma}\mathbf{W}_k = \mathbf{W}_k\mathbf{\Lambda}_k,
\end{equation}
and projects features as
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{z} = \mathbf{W}_k^\top \mathbf{x}, \quad \mathbf{z}\in\mathbb{R}^{k}.
\end{equation}
The dimensionality $k$ is treated as a hyperparameter chosen on the validation set.

\subsection{K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)}
KNN is a non-parametric method that predicts the label of a query point using majority voting among its $k$ nearest neighbors in the training set. After PCA, distances are computed in the reduced space. Denote by $\mathcal{N}_k(\mathbf{z})$ the index set of the $k$ closest training points to $\mathbf{z}$ under Euclidean distance. The prediction is
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}(\mathbf{z}) = \arg\max_{c\in\{0,\dots,9\}} \sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_k(\mathbf{z})} \mathbb{I}(y_i=c),
\end{equation}
where $\mathbb{I}(\cdot)$ is the indicator function. The neighborhood size $k$ is selected via validation.

\subsection{Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)}
LDA is a generative classifier that assumes class-conditional Gaussian densities with a shared covariance:
\begin{equation}
p(\mathbf{z}\mid y=c)=\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{z};\boldsymbol{\mu}_c,\mathbf{\Sigma}), \qquad p(y=c)=\pi_c,
\end{equation}
where $\boldsymbol{\mu}_c$ is the class mean, $\mathbf{\Sigma}$ is the pooled covariance, and $\pi_c$ is the class prior. The LDA discriminant function is
\begin{equation}
\delta_c(\mathbf{z})=\mathbf{z}^\top \mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mu}_c - \frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{\mu}_c^\top\mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mu}_c + \log \pi_c,
\end{equation}
and the prediction is $\hat{y}(\mathbf{z})=\arg\max_c \delta_c(\mathbf{z})$. We apply PCA prior to LDA to stabilize covariance estimation in high dimensions.

\subsection{Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)}
QDA generalizes LDA by allowing class-specific covariance matrices:
\begin{equation}
p(\mathbf{z}\mid y=c)=\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{z};\boldsymbol{\mu}_c,\mathbf{\Sigma}_c), \qquad p(y=c)=\pi_c.
\end{equation}
Its discriminant function is quadratic:
\begin{equation}
\delta_c(\mathbf{z}) = -\frac{1}{2}\log|\mathbf{\Sigma}_c|
-\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{z}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_c)^\top \mathbf{\Sigma}_c^{-1}(\mathbf{z}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_c) + \log \pi_c.
\end{equation}
The predicted class is $\hat{y}(\mathbf{z})=\arg\max_c \delta_c(\mathbf{z})$. Since QDA requires estimating $\mathbf{\Sigma}_c$ for each class and is more sensitive to noise, we operate in the PCA-reduced space to reduce variance and improve numerical stability.

\subsection{Random Forest}
Random Forest constructs an ensemble of decision trees $\{T_b\}_{b=1}^{B}$ trained on bootstrap samples, and at each split considers a random subset of features. For an input $\mathbf{x}$, each tree outputs a class prediction $T_b(\mathbf{x})\in\{0,\dots,9\}$, and the forest prediction is obtained by majority voting:
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}(\mathbf{x}) = \arg\max_{c\in\{0,\dots,9\}} \sum_{b=1}^{B} \mathbb{I}\big(T_b(\mathbf{x})=c\big).
\end{equation}
We train Random Forest on the preprocessed 1024-D features (without PCA) to preserve potentially informative coordinate interactions. Hyperparameters such as $B$, maximum depth, and minimum samples per leaf are tuned on the validation set.

\subsection{Deep Neural Network Baseline (MLP)}
As a deep learning baseline, we use a multilayer perceptron that outputs class probabilities via a softmax layer. Given logits $\mathbf{g}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\in\mathbb{R}^{10}$, the predicted probability for class $c$ is
\begin{equation}
p_\theta(y=c\mid \mathbf{x})=\frac{\exp(g_{\theta,c}(\mathbf{x}))}{\sum_{j=0}^{9}\exp(g_{\theta,j}(\mathbf{x}))}.
\end{equation}
We train the network by minimizing the empirical cross-entropy loss on the training set:
\begin{equation}
\min_\theta \ \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N} \Big(-\log p_\theta(y_i\mid \mathbf{x}_i)\Big).
\end{equation}
To improve robustness to test-time corruption, we optionally employ train-time noise augmentation by perturbing inputs as
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{x}_i + \alpha \boldsymbol{\eta}_i,\qquad \boldsymbol{\eta}_i\sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}),
\end{equation}
and optimize the same loss using $\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_i$ in place of $\mathbf{x}_i$ during training. Architectural and optimization hyperparameters (e.g., depth/width, dropout, learning rate, weight decay) are selected using validation performance.
```

```latex
\section{Model assessment and selection}
To obtain a reliable estimate of generalization performance and to select hyperparameters in a principled manner, we combine hold-out validation with hyperparameter search and cross-validation/repeated runs. All selection procedures are conducted using only the training/validation data; the test set is used exclusively for final reporting.

\subsection{Evaluation metrics}
We use \textbf{classification accuracy} as the primary metric, consistent with the project objective. In addition, we report \textbf{Macro-F1} to account for per-class performance in a class-agnostic manner:
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Macro\text{-}F1} = \frac{1}{C}\sum_{c=1}^{C} \mathrm{F1}_c, \quad C=10,
\end{equation}
where $\mathrm{F1}_c$ is the F1-score computed for class $c$ using a one-vs-rest formulation. Accuracy is used for model ranking, while Macro-F1 serves as a complementary indicator of balanced performance across classes.

\subsection{Hold-out validation with hyperparameter search}
We split the original training set into a training subset and a validation subset using a stratified hold-out strategy. Hyperparameters are optimized via \textbf{grid search} for low-dimensional search spaces and \textbf{random search} for higher-dimensional spaces. For each candidate configuration $\lambda\in\Lambda$, a model is trained on the training subset and evaluated on the validation subset; the selected configuration is
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{*}=\arg\max_{\lambda\in\Lambda} \ \mathrm{Acc}_{\mathrm{val}}(\lambda),
\end{equation}
with Macro-F1 used as a tie-breaker (or as the primary criterion when accuracy differences are marginal). The searched ranges include, for example, $k$ in KNN, the PCA dimension $d$, regularization/shrinkage parameters for (Q)DA (if applicable), the number/depth of trees for Random Forest, and architecture/optimization hyperparameters for the MLP (e.g., hidden size, learning rate, weight decay, dropout).

\subsection{Cross-validation / repeated experiments}
To reduce the variance induced by a single split and to increase the credibility of comparisons, we additionally perform \textbf{$K$-fold stratified cross-validation} (or repeated hold-out runs) for the best-performing candidates. In $K$-fold CV, the data are partitioned into $K$ folds with preserved class proportions; each fold is used once as validation while the remaining $K-1$ folds are used for training. We report the mean and standard deviation of the metric:
\begin{equation}
\bar{m}=\frac{1}{K}\sum_{t=1}^{K} m^{(t)},\qquad
s=\sqrt{\frac{1}{K-1}\sum_{t=1}^{K}\left(m^{(t)}-\bar{m}\right)^2},
\end{equation}
where $m^{(t)}$ denotes the validation performance on fold $t$. This protocol provides a more stable estimate of expected generalization and supports robust model selection.

\subsection{Overfitting diagnosis and early stopping (deep model)}
For the deep learning model, we monitor training and validation curves (loss and accuracy) to diagnose overfitting. We apply \textbf{early stopping} by terminating training when the validation metric does not improve for a fixed patience window, and we restore the model parameters corresponding to the best validation performance. This procedure serves as an implicit regularizer and improves generalization under the noisy test distribution.
```

```latex
\section{Experiments and results}
We conduct controlled experiments to compare the proposed methods under a unified preprocessing pipeline. For KNN, LDA, and QDA, we additionally apply PCA and vary the retained dimensionality to study how low-rank representations affect predictive performance. Random Forest (RF) and the neural network baseline are trained on the preprocessed features without PCA. For each method, we report the \emph{best} configuration selected on the validation set. The summary is given in Table~\ref{tab:best-results}, while Fig.~\ref{fig:pca-dim-effect} illustrates the performance trends across PCA dimensions.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Best validation performance for each method.}
\label{tab:best-results}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{PCA dimension} & \textbf{Accuracy} \\
\midrule
KNN & 50 & \textbf{0.83484} \\
LDA & 60 & 0.77542 \\
QDA & 50 & 0.78650 \\
RF  & -- & 0.73816 \\
Neural Network & -- & 0.81268 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
% \includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{figures/pca_dim_effect.pdf}
\caption{Effect of PCA dimensionality on validation accuracy for KNN/LDA/QDA (trained on Preprocess+PCA features).}
\label{fig:pca-dim-effect}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Effect of PCA dimensionality.}
As shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:pca-dim-effect}, KNN benefits from increasing the PCA dimension from 20 to 50 (0.80664 $\rightarrow$ 0.83484), but degrades at 60 (0.82275), suggesting an optimal bias--variance trade-off near 50 components: overly aggressive compression removes discriminative information, whereas retaining more components may reintroduce noisy directions that harm neighborhood retrieval. LDA and QDA exhibit comparatively mild sensitivity to PCA dimensionality, with small improvements from 20 to 50/60, which is consistent with improved class separability while keeping covariance estimation stable in a reduced space.

\paragraph{Model comparison.}
Among all evaluated methods, KNN achieves the highest accuracy (0.83484) at PCA dimension 50. The neural network baseline performs competitively (0.81268) but does not surpass the best KNN setting under the current configuration. QDA consistently outperforms LDA, indicating that class-specific covariance modeling provides beneficial flexibility on this dataset. RF yields the lowest accuracy (0.73816), suggesting that its inductive bias is less well matched to the feature representation and the noise characteristics in this task.

\paragraph{Selected configuration.}
Based on validation performance, we select \textbf{KNN with PCA dimension 50} as the best-performing non-deep-learning model for subsequent analysis.
