\subsection{Additional analysis and implications}
Beyond ablations, we provide further discussion on why certain methods perform better under the noisy test setting and what limitations remain.

\textbf{Why KNN benefits most from PCA and robust scaling.}
KNN relies directly on pairwise distances; hence its performance is strongly affected by heterogeneous feature scales and by the concentration of distances in high dimensions. Robust scaling reduces the influence of heavy-tailed coordinates and outliers, while PCA mitigates the curse of dimensionality by projecting data onto a compact subspace that preserves the dominant signal variance. The observed optimum around 50 principal components suggests that overly aggressive compression removes discriminative structure, whereas retaining too many components reintroduces noise-dominated directions that impair neighborhood retrieval.

\textbf{LDA vs.\ QDA: flexibility vs.\ estimation stability.}
Across PCA settings, QDA consistently outperforms LDA, indicating that class-specific covariance structure is informative in this feature space. However, QDA is more sensitive to covariance estimation error; PCA acts as an implicit regularizer by reducing the effective dimensionality, which likely explains why QDA remains stable and competitive despite the noisy conditions.

\textbf{Why Random Forest underperforms in this setting.}
RF yields lower accuracy than the distance- and Gaussian-based models. A plausible explanation is that the 1024-D representation is relatively dense and smooth, while tree-based methods partition the feature space via axis-aligned splits, which can be suboptimal when discriminative information is distributed across many correlated dimensions. In addition, test-time noise can perturb split decisions near thresholds, degrading the reliability of individual trees even when averaged in an ensemble.

\textbf{Effectiveness and limitations of train-time noise augmentation.}
Noise augmentation provides a consistent improvement, supporting the hypothesis that the task involves a train--test shift induced by additive feature perturbations. Nonetheless, augmentation with isotropic Gaussian noise is only an approximation of the unknown test corruption; if the true noise is structured (e.g., feature-dependent variance or correlated perturbations), more targeted augmentation or robust objectives may further improve performance.

\textbf{Error patterns and class overlap.}
