\subsection{Data preprocessing}
\label{sec:data-preprocess}
\textbf{Feature-wise standardization.}
The feature dimensions exhibit non-uniform scales and heterogeneous dispersion, which can cause a small subset of coordinates to dominate distance- or margin-based learning objectives and lead to unstable optimization. Standardization enforces a comparable scale across dimensions and improves numerical conditioning and model comparability across methods. We compute the per-dimension mean $\mu$ and standard deviation $\sigma$ on the training set only, and transform all splits (train/validation/test) via
\begin{equation}
x'_{d}=\frac{x_{d}-\mu_{d}}{\sigma_{d}+\epsilon},
\end{equation}
where $\epsilon$ is a small constant for numerical stability.
\textbf{Outlier-aware scaling.}
The feature distributions exhibit heavy-tailed behavior with frequent outliers; in such cases, mean/variance estimates can be overly influenced by extreme values, potentially degrading robustness under test-time noise. Robust scaling mitigates the impact of outliers by relying on robust location and scale statistics. Using training data only, we estimate the per-dimension median $m_d$ and interquartile range $\mathrm{IQR}_d$, and apply the transformation
\begin{equation}
x'_{d}=\frac{x_{d}-m_{d}}{\mathrm{IQR}_{d}+\epsilon}.
\end{equation}
The same transformation is then applied to the validation and test sets. We treat the choice between standardization and robust scaling as a preprocessing option selected based on validation performance.
\textbf{Train-time noise augmentation.}
Since the test features are corrupted by random noise, the learning problem involves a train--test distribution shift. Injecting noise during training acts as data augmentation and regularization, encouraging locally smooth decision functions and improving robustness to additive perturbations. During training, each input vector is perturbed as
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{x}+\alpha \boldsymbol{\eta}, \quad \boldsymbol{\eta}\sim\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}),
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ controls the noise intensity. The perturbation is applied only to training samples (not validation/test), and $\alpha$ is tuned using validation performance.
\section{Methods}
We evaluate a diverse set of classifiers to study both predictive performance and robustness under feature noise. All models are trained on the preprocessed features described in Section~\ref{sec:data-preprocess}. For methods that are sensitive to the curse of dimensionality or rely on covariance estimation, we further apply PCA as a dimensionality reduction step. Consequently, we adopt two input configurations: (i) \emph{Preprocess+PCA} for KNN, LDA, and QDA, and (ii) \emph{Preprocess only} for Random Forest and the deep learning baseline.
\subsection{K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)}
KNN is a non-parametric method that predicts the label of a query point using majority voting among its $k$ nearest neighbors in the training set. After PCA, distances are computed in the reduced space. Denote by $\mathcal{N}_k(\mathbf{z})$ the index set of the $k$ closest training points to $\mathbf{z}$ under Euclidean distance. The prediction is
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}(\mathbf{z}) = \arg\max_{c\in\{0,\dots,9\}} \sum_{i\in\mathcal{N}_k(\mathbf{z})} \mathbb{I}(y_i=c),
\end{equation}
where $\mathbb{I}(\cdot)$ is the indicator function. The neighborhood size $k$ is selected via validation.
\subsection{Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)}
LDA is a generative classifier that assumes class-conditional Gaussian densities with a shared covariance:
\begin{equation}
p(\mathbf{z}\mid y=c)=\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{z};\boldsymbol{\mu}_c,\mathbf{\Sigma}), \qquad p(y=c)=\pi_c,
\end{equation}
where $\boldsymbol{\mu}_c$ is the class mean, $\mathbf{\Sigma}$ is the pooled covariance, and $\pi_c$ is the class prior. The LDA discriminant function is
\begin{equation}
\delta_c(\mathbf{z})=\mathbf{z}^\top \mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mu}_c - \frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{\mu}_c^\top\mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mu}_c + \log \pi_c,
\end{equation}
and the prediction is $\hat{y}(\mathbf{z})=\arg\max_c \delta_c(\mathbf{z})$. We apply PCA prior to LDA to stabilize covariance estimation in high dimensions.
\subsection{Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)}
QDA generalizes LDA by allowing class-specific covariance matrices:
\begin{equation}
p(\mathbf{z}\mid y=c)=\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{z};\boldsymbol{\mu}_c,\mathbf{\Sigma}_c), \qquad p(y=c)=\pi_c.
\end{equation}
Its discriminant function is quadratic:
\begin{equation}
\delta_c(\mathbf{z}) = -\frac{1}{2}\log|\mathbf{\Sigma}_c|
-\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{z}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_c)^\top \mathbf{\Sigma}_c^{-1}(\mathbf{z}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_c) + \log \pi_c.
\end{equation}
The predicted class is $\hat{y}(\mathbf{z})=\arg\max_c \delta_c(\mathbf{z})$. Since QDA requires estimating $\mathbf{\Sigma}_c$ for each class and is more sensitive to noise, we operate in the PCA-reduced space to reduce variance and improve numerical stability.
\subsection{Random Forest}
Random Forest constructs an ensemble of decision trees $\{T_b\}_{b=1}^{B}$ trained on bootstrap samples, and at each split considers a random subset of features. For an input $\mathbf{x}$, each tree outputs a class prediction $T_b(\mathbf{x})\in\{0,\dots,9\}$, and the forest prediction is obtained by majority voting:
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}(\mathbf{x}) = \arg\max_{c\in\{0,\dots,9\}} \sum_{b=1}^{B} \mathbb{I}\big(T_b(\mathbf{x})=c\big).
\end{equation}
We train Random Forest on the preprocessed 1024-D features (without PCA) to preserve potentially informative coordinate interactions. Hyperparameters such as $B$, maximum depth, and minimum samples per leaf are tuned on the validation set.
\subsection{Deep Neural Network Baseline (MLP)}
As a deep learning baseline, we use a multilayer perceptron that outputs class probabilities via a softmax layer. Given logits $\mathbf{g}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\in\mathbb{R}^{10}$, the predicted probability for class $c$ is
\begin{equation}
p_\theta(y=c\mid \mathbf{x})=\frac{\exp(g_{\theta,c}(\mathbf{x}))}{\sum_{j=0}^{9}\exp(g_{\theta,j}(\mathbf{x}))}.
\end{equation}
We train the network by minimizing the empirical cross-entropy loss on the training set:
\begin{equation}
\min_\theta \ \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N} \Big(-\log p_\theta(y_i\mid \mathbf{x}_i)\Big).
\end{equation}
To improve robustness to test-time corruption, we optionally employ train-time noise augmentation by perturbing inputs as
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{x}_i + \alpha \boldsymbol{\eta}_i,\qquad \boldsymbol{\eta}_i\sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}),
\end{equation}
and optimize the same loss using $\tilde{\mathbf{x}}_i$ in place of $\mathbf{x}_i$ during training. Architectural and optimization hyperparameters (e.g., depth/width, dropout, learning rate, weight decay) are selected using validation performance.
\section{Model assessment and selection}
To obtain a reliable estimate of generalization performance and to select hyperparameters in a principled manner, we combine hold-out validation with hyperparameter search and cross-validation/repeated runs. All selection procedures are conducted using only the training/validation data; the test set is used exclusively for final reporting. We use \textbf{classification accuracy} as the primary metric, consistent with the project objective.
\subsection{Hold-out validation with hyperparameter search}
We split the original training set into a training subset and a validation subset using a stratified hold-out strategy. Hyperparameters are optimized via \textbf{grid search} for low-dimensional search spaces and \textbf{random search} for higher-dimensional spaces. For each candidate configuration $\lambda\in\Lambda$, a model is trained on the training subset and evaluated on the validation subset; the selected configuration is
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{*}=\arg\max_{\lambda\in\Lambda} \ \mathrm{Acc}_{\mathrm{val}}(\lambda),
\end{equation}
with Macro-F1 used as a tie-breaker (or as the primary criterion when accuracy differences are marginal). The searched ranges include, for example, $k$ in KNN, the PCA dimension $d$, regularization/shrinkage parameters for (Q)DA (if applicable), the number/depth of trees for Random Forest, and architecture/optimization hyperparameters for the MLP (e.g., hidden size, learning rate, weight decay, dropout).
\subsection{Cross-validation}
To reduce the variance induced by a single split and to increase the credibility of comparisons, we additionally perform \textbf{$K$-fold stratified cross-validation} (or repeated hold-out runs) for the best-performing candidates. In $K$-fold CV, the data are partitioned into $K$ folds with preserved class proportions; each fold is used once as validation while the remaining $K-1$ folds are used for training. We report the mean and standard deviation of the metric:
\begin{equation}
\bar{m}=\frac{1}{K}\sum_{t=1}^{K} m^{(t)},\qquad
s=\sqrt{\frac{1}{K-1}\sum_{t=1}^{K}\left(m^{(t)}-\bar{m}\right)^2},
\end{equation}
where $m^{(t)}$ denotes the validation performance on fold $t$. This protocol provides a more stable estimate of expected generalization and supports robust model selection.
\subsection{Overfitting diagnosis and early stopping (deep model)}
For the deep learning model, we monitor training and validation curves (loss and accuracy) to diagnose overfitting. We apply \textbf{early stopping} by terminating training when the validation metric does not improve for a fixed patience window, and we restore the model parameters corresponding to the best validation performance. This procedure serves as an implicit regularizer and improves generalization under the noisy test distribution.
